    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You make a very valid point. The role of the secular state is indeed to be neutral and impartial, ensuring that all individuals and organizations are treated equally under the law. If uniformity within the legal system conflicts with these principles by imposing a one-size-fits-all rule without considering deeply held religious convictions, it raises questions about true neutrality and the extent of individual or group freedom. The state must find ways to accommodate religious practices as far as possible without compromising fundamental rights and the overarching legal framework. Once individual or group freedoms begin to diminish, even indirectly through enforced uniformity, there seems to be less reason for a law to be considered secular. However, maintaining this neutrality also ensures that private religious freedoms do not impinge on the rights of others, thereby safeguarding a balanced society within which diverse beliefs can coexist.",
      "source": "target",
